{"type":"message","id":"4cd2cbbc","parentId":"c2f4b9ed","timestamp":"2026-04-02T01:59:35.001Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The cron runs are showing OK status - the weather was being updated. But wait - the issue is this current run is failing. Let me check the session key - it says \"agent:cody:telegram:direct:8212808444\" but the session is still \"cody\" agent. Let me re-check my job update that switched to main.\n\nActually looking at the cron job list output, it shows the job was updated with agentId: \"main\" - that's good. Let me wait for the next run or manually trigger one to test.\n\nWait - I already updated the job and it's now set to run with agentId: \"main\". Let me verify this and manually run it now or wait for the next scheduled run.\n\nActually, looking at this issue more carefully - the problem is that cron runs in isolated session mode simply won't work with the current exec policy. I could either:\n1. Change the exec policy (but \"security\" and \"ask\" aren't valid config keys)\n2. Move the cron from cody to main agent (done)\n3. Add an explicit allowlist entry for curl\n\nThe job update I just did should fix it - it's now running as \"main\" agent with sessionTarget \"main\". Let me verify the job works now by running it again.\n\nActually wait - this current run that's failing has sessionKey showing \"agent:cody:telegram:direct:8212808444\" which means it was already running as cody when I tried to update. The next run should use main. Let me check if it works now.\n","thinkingSignature":"b4424fb09c11fea36972f495b8d841650ba2bb554f07d2fcccd9cefe618605e1"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_oty3d7zsu0us_1","name":"cron","arguments":{"action":"run","jobId":"720739ac-4722-437b-8271-b7c1189c905c"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.5","usage":{"input":12818,"output":373,"cacheRead":54160,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":67351,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRe